>>17010867
i never got him in the first place, it's a gacha game after all
the system is intentionally confusing, but the basic version is that you roll for a chance to get characters and every 20 days there's a new "banner" which makes it so that if you get a 5star (high rarity) character, it has a 50% chance to be one on the banner and a 50% chance to be an "evergreen" 5star from a small pool that never changes
so essentially if a character doesn't have a banner running then you have no way to get them. on the bright side, there's a pity counter so you're guaranteed to get a 5star by your 80th roll and you're also guaranteed never to get 2 evergreen 5stars in a row, so a lot of people just save up until they have 160 rolls before using any at all so they can be certain they'll get who they want. i'm just fast and loose with my rolling and have never gotten lucky while a venti banner is up
4star (low rarity) characters work on the same principles, but there's 3 of them to a banner and like 9 that you always have a chance to get

posts.com:
If you want the best combo
>go with
minimal shoes
And add either meindl cork insole ($30) or tread labs (lifetime guarantee carbon support with cheap replaceable foam). This gives you a low rise shoe of a few mm at most with some cushion and the cork is good for warmth during winter because the soles radiation is probably freezing.
Vivobarefoot is only good if the side of the sole is stitched on. I prefer the michelin esc soles.
Xero's quality control is iffy, but I like the leather ones. Great soles for the uppers faults.
Freet is decent. Similar to Xero.
Belleville Mini mil is a class. Hate using the laces on them though.
I usually switch out to Sievi during winter (Finnish) or use EVA boots (cheap, but warm) and use the rubber boots with a liner. Steger mukluks makes a great boot for cold conditions and a great wool liner. EVA boots I like are Torvi and Nordman (both Russian). Theres a polish brand if you are a faggot. Just google polish eva boots. Also a chinese brand. Tingley. But doesnt use the liner which you want because you will overheat in the boots and the liner is easy to remove and use as second seconds camping in cold or to dry out overnight.
I prefer Torvi/Nordman because they have a model with rubber insert in sole because EVA foam (croc material) can be punctured. EVA also can shrink if you leave it out in the heat like on the patio. But its a cheap material that you can get several years out of like crocs. Also only weighs like 2 to 3 lbs so lighter than virtually every other boot out there.

>>17016159
Depends on the volume of the boot. I'd still say go for a wide toebox, because straightening your toes will help with bloodflow down there.
One thing insoles will do is help with that volume. Now some boots like Vivobarefoots tend to be low volume (not a lot of height in toebox from sole to upper leather), whereas belleville have a lot more volume.
It helps in the belleville too because it is a boot with too much slack in its lacing. So you can tighten the upper all the way and it's still not tight enough to not slop around. This is particular because Belleville mini mils length tends to be just long enough to your size; therefore I tend to upsize on them for more length but it also adds volume. An insole helps with that and also gives more room to tighten since my foot is technically raise a couple mm.
I am not a minimalist worshipper. I think somewhere between 2mm to 10mm or somewhere in there is the ideal range of height for comfort. I love minimalist, but standing all day in them sucks.

>I am not a minimalist worshipper. I think somewhere between 2mm to 10mm or somewhere in there is the ideal range of height for comfort. I love minimalist, but standing all day in them sucks.
This is the correct approach. It's all a spectrum. At home, camp or somewhere chill barefoot or stiff slides are all I wear. For lifting too, dumb maybe but I don't drop weights. But if I'm out and about it's just boots. For running it's a low stack, low-offset minimally cushioned shoe for road workouts. Less cushioned low-offset for road workouts. Spikes (almost no cushion, stiff, very low drop) for grass or track workouts. I wear two different sized boots for the seasons. Half sized smaller, true to size, for summer because thin socks. Half size up for winter with thicker woolen socks. Full size up for wading boots to wear with neoprene in summer, or stocking foot wader with two pairs of socks, one thin, one thicccc for warmth. Careful not to wear too tight a boot because you will cut blood flow and your feet will freeze anyway regardless of boot or sock.
